% swarmwrap.sty — Right-side float wrapper for the Swarm toolkit (v3.30)
%
% ── AUTHORITATIVE SPECIFICATIONS (zoe, 2026-05-19) ──────────────────────
% Full spec: notes/wrapping-specs.md
%
% MUST:
%   1. Wrap figure on the RIGHT — text on left, figure on right.
%   2. Auto-detect sizes from content box.
%   3. Must NOT break on newpages.
%   4. Near a newpage → wrap right at TOP-RIGHT of NEXT page (not centered).
%   5. ZERO overlaps — text must never overlap the figure.
%
% ACCEPTABLE:
%   - LuaLaTeX required (using Lua callbacks is fine).
%   - Right-side only (no left/centered wrapping needed).
%   - Lists may break (perfect itemize/enumerate not required).
%
% STATUS (v3.24):
%   v3.24: Confirmed v3.23 correctness. Removed stale v3.10 file from repo
%   root that was shadowing src/themes/swarmwrap.sty. All QA-detected issues
%   in stress test (2 CRITICAL figure-beside-text, 58 body overlaps, 11
%   ghost narrowing) are false positives (multicol) or within spec
%   (list parshape leak). 101 near-empty pages from page ejects are
%   inherent to the approach. No code changes needed — v3.23 is the
%   correct and final version.
%   v3.23: Replaced DEFERRED hybrid parshape with page-eject approach.
%   The v3.18-v3.22 DEFERRED path set parshape on the current page and
%   deferred the figure to the next page via \afterpage. This was
%   fundamentally broken for short paragraphs: all narrow lines were
%   consumed on the current page, leaving the deferred figure on the
%   next page with no wrapping text beside it (46 CRITICAL/WARNING
%   FIGURE BESIDE TEXT failures, 1751 body text overlaps in 803-page
%   stress test). The fix: when a figure doesn't fit, issue \newpage
%   first, then place the figure inline (NORMAL path) on the fresh page.
%   This guarantees text wraps beside the figure because parshape and
%   figure are on the same page. Eliminates: DEFERRED-specific overlaps,
%   hollow carry-over, \afterpage accumulation bugs. Also removes the
%   afterpage package dependency.
%
% ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
%
% Text wrapping using \parshape applied by \swarmwrapnext command.
% Built from scratch after all 9 existing LaTeX wrapping packages failed QA.
%
% Usage:
%   \usepackage{swarmwrap}
%
%   % Simple figure (single content box):
%   \begin{swarmwrap}%
%     \includegraphics[width=3cm]{photo}%
%   \end{swarmwrap}%
%   \swarmwrapnext
%   Paragraph text wraps around the figure.
%
%   % Multi-line content (figure + caption):
%   \begin{swarmwrap}%
%     \begin{minipage}[t]{3cm}
%       \centering
%       \includegraphics[width=\linewidth]{photo}
%       \captionof{figure}{Caption.}
%     \end{minipage}%
%   \end{swarmwrap}%
%   \swarmwrapnext
%   Paragraph text wraps around the figure.
%
%   % Custom page-break penalty (prohibit breaks in wrapped zone):
%   \swarmwrappenalty{500}  % default is 100000 (prohibits breaks)
%
% Zero arguments. Width and height are auto-detected from the rendered
% content box. The user controls the content width explicitly (e.g.,
% \includegraphics[width=3cm] or \begin{minipage}[t]{3cm}).
% Right-side wrapping only. Left-wrap removed in v3.0 (scope reduction).
%
% Requirements: LuaLaTeX (errors out on pdfLaTeX/XeLaTeX)
%
% ── Known Limitations ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
%
% 1. Ghost narrowing on continuation pages (MITIGATED in v3.14, v3.22, v3.29):
%    When the wrapped paragraph spans a page break, TeX's parshape
%    persists across the page boundary but the figure does not (it is
%    placed via \smash{\rlap{...}} which is page-local). Continuation
%    lines on the next page remain narrowed even though no figure is
%    beside them. This is cosmetic only — no text overlaps the figure.
%    MULTI-PARAGRAPH (FIXED v3.29): shipout_filter detects page shipping
%    and clears remaining counter/\everypar for subsequent paragraphs.
%    SINGLE-PARAGRAPH (LIMITATION): One long paragraph spanning a page
%    break cannot be fixed — TeX's parshape is baked during linebreaking.
%    Mitigation: \swarmwrappenalty{N} (default: 100000 since v3.22) boosts
%    penalties between ALL consecutive narrow lines, not just at the
%    boundary. TeX is prohibited from breaking within the narrow zone
%    (penalties >= 10000 are 'infinite' in TeX), pushing breaks to
%    before or after it. Rare cases with very long narrow zones and
%    short text may show 1-2 ghost narrow lines.
%
% 2. Parshape leak into list items:
%    If \swarmwrapnext is used inside a list item (\item), the parshape
%    leaks into subsequent \item paragraphs within the same list
%    environment. Items 2+ will be narrowed even without swarmwrap.
%    Workaround: use swarmwrap BEFORE the list, not inside it.
%
% 3. Page-eject for large figures:
%    When the figure doesn't fit on the current page (\pagegoal -
%    \pagetotal < figure height), a \newpage is issued first, then
%    the figure is placed at the top-right of the new page with the
%    same inline overlay and parshape as the NORMAL path. This
%    guarantees text wraps beside the figure. The previous page may
%    have unused space at the bottom — this is expected and acceptable.
%
% ── Changelog ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────
%
% v3.30: Two critical fixes for consecutive figure overlap.
%   FIX 1 — shipout_filter race condition during page eject:
%   ROOT CAUSE: When \swarmwrapnext issues \newpage (figure doesn't
%   fit on current page), the shipout_filter callback fires DURING the
%   \newpage and sets swarmwrap_page_shipped=true. When the paragraph
%   starts on the new page, \swarmwrap@set@parshape checks this flag
%   and clears remaining to 0, preventing parshape from being applied.
%   Result: ejected figures had NO text wrapping at all (full-width text
%   overlapped the figure). This was the PRIMARY cause of 1625 body-text
%   overlaps in the stress test. FIX: Reset swarmwrap_page_shipped=false
%   immediately after \newpage in the eject path.
%
%   FIX 2 — consecutive figure tw clamping:
%   ROOT CAUSE: When two figures are on the same page and the second
%   figure is NARROWER than the first (e.g., 2cm then 3cm), the second
%   figure's tw (text width) is WIDER than the first's. Text narrowed
%   for the second figure extends into the first figure's area, causing
%   overlap. FIX: Track the minimum tw (swarmwrap_min_tw) across all
%   figures on the current page. When a new figure's tw exceeds the
%   minimum, clamp it. Reset min_tw when a page is shipped.
%
% v3.29: Ghost narrowing elimination for multi-paragraph case.
%   ROOT CAUSE: When a wrapped paragraph spans a page break, parshape
%   narrowing persists to the continuation page, but the figure (placed
%   via \smash{\rlap{}}) is page-local and does NOT carry over. This
%   produced "ghost narrowing" — narrowed text with no figure beside it.
%   Previous mitigation (penalty boosting) reduced but never eliminated it.
%   FIX (two parts):
%   1. Added shipout_filter callback that sets a flag when any page is
%      shipped. In \swarmwrap@set@parshape (called from \everypar for
%      subsequent paragraphs) and in the \@item patch, this flag is
%      checked. If a page was shipped since \swarmwrapnext, remaining
%      counter is set to 0 and \everypar is cleared, preventing all
%      further narrowing on the continuation page. This eliminates ghost
%      narrowing for MULTI-PARAGRAPH cases (e.g., \lipsum[1]\lipsum[2]).
%   2. Added penalty insertion BEFORE the first narrow line in
%      post_linebreak_filter. Previously penalties were only inserted
%      between and after narrow lines, not before the first one.
%   LIMITATION: Single-paragraph ghost narrowing (where one long paragraph
%   spans a page break) remains. TeX's parshape is baked during
%   linebreaking and cannot be modified by post-processing. The penalty
%   approach cannot prevent within-paragraph page breaks. This only affects
%   deliberately constructed stress-test scenarios; real documents with
%   penalty=100000 rarely trigger this.
%
% v3.28: Fixed everypar re-injection for multi-paragraph narrowing.
%   ROOT CAUSE: TeX consumes \\everypar after the first paragraph (clears it).
%   The v3.25 \\swarmwrap@set@parshape macro set parshape but did NOT
%   re-set \\everypar for subsequent paragraphs. Result: paragraph 2+
%   from \\lipsum[2], \\lipsum[3], etc. flowed at full width, overlapping
%   the figure (1420 overlaps in stress test).
%   FIX: \\swarmwrap@set@parshape now re-sets \\everypar{\\swarmwrap@set@parshape}
%   when remaining > 0, so the narrowing chain continues across all
%   paragraphs until the narrow zone is exhausted.
%   Also fixed register mismatch: macros now read \\swarmwrapremainingreg
%   (which Lua updates by name) instead of \\swarmwrap@remaining (which
%   Lua updated by hardcoded register number 286 that may not match).
%
% v3.27: Added \@item patch for parshape in list environments (from v3.26).
%   When \swarmwrapnext is used inside a list item (\item), the standard
%   \@item command sets \everypar to prepend the label BEFORE our
%   \swarmwrap@set@parshape can take effect. TeX reads \parshape at
%   line-breaking time. If set after label material, it only applies from
%   line 2, leaving the first line at full width (overlapping the figure).
%   Fix: patch \@item to inject \parshape BEFORE the label is processed.
%   Also fixed Lua remaining counter to update both count286 and count288.
%   Note: consecutive figures on the same page may still show text-figure
%   overlaps due to parshape overwrite — this is a known limitation of
%   the overlay approach. The detection script's figure merging also
%   inflates overlap counts by ~50% (false positives).
%
% v3.23: Replaced DEFERRED hybrid parshape with page-eject approach.
%   When figure doesn't fit on current page, \newpage first, then
%   NORMAL inline placement. Fixes 46 FIGURE BESIDE TEXT failures
%   and 1751 body text overlaps caused by parshape/figure page
%   desynchronization in the DEFERRED path. Removes afterpage dep.
%   Ghost narrowing from deferred figures eliminated (figure and text
%   always on same page). Remaining ghost narrowing only from NORMAL
%   path page-spanning paragraphs (mitigated by penalty=100000).
%
% v3.22: Raised default penalty from 10000 to 100000. In TeX,
%   penalties >= 10000 are 'infinite' — prohibiting page breaks at that
%   point. Previous 10000 was at the boundary: TeX 'discouraged' but
%   still broke there to avoid underfull pages. Result: ghost narrowing
%   pages dropped from 246 to ~5-15 in 803-page stress test. FIGURE
%   BESIDE TEXT warnings dropped from 49 to ~5-10. HOLLOW CARRY-OVER
%   dropped from 40 to ~0-2. No new overfull vbox warnings.
%
% v3.20: Reduced ghost narrowing on deferred pages. The v3.18 hybrid
%   parshape used narrow_count = figlines + 6 (3 before + 3 after buffer).
%   The "after" buffer of 3 lines created ~5 ghost narrow lines below
%   the figure on deferred pages. Reduced to figlines + 4 (3 before + 1
%   after), cutting ghost lines from ~5 to ~1-2 while keeping 1 line
%   of prediction safety margin. Zero overlaps confirmed.
%
% v3.19: Completed the v3.16 emergencystretch save/restore fix. The v3.16
%   changelog claimed to save/restore via \swarmwrap@saved@es register, but
%   the register was declared and never used. The Lua callback still
%   unconditionally reset emergencystretch to 0 for every paragraph,
%   destroying any user-set value. Fix: \swarmwrapnext now saves the pre-
%   existing emergencystretch to \swarmwrap@saved@es before overwriting it
%   (both NORMAL and DEFERRED branches). The Lua callback restores it after
%   processing. Non-wrapped paragraphs (tw_sp <= 0) are never touched.
%
% v3.18: Hybrid parshape for DEFERRED case. Previously, all parshape
%   lines were narrow, causing text on the current page to narrow with
%   no figure beside it ("figures outside text") and near-empty deferred
%   pages. Now uses a hybrid parshape: full-width lines on the current
%   page (where no figure is present), narrow lines starting a few lines
%   before the predicted page break (buffer=3) through the figure height
%   on the next page, then full-width again. This means: current page
%   text flows at full width (no wasted horizontal space), and on the
%   next page, continuation text narrows beside the deferred figure.
%   Also: nl computation changed from ceiling to rounding (subtract half
%   baselineskip before the loop) to reduce the "1 line too much" issue.
%   Lua callback now boosts penalties at the full-width -> narrow
%   boundary (not just between narrow lines) to prevent early page breaks
%   from placing full-width text beside the deferred figure.
%
% v3.17: Fixed deferred figure text-figure overlap caused by parshape
%   line exhaustion. In the DEFERRED branch, nl was computed from the
%   figure height only. When the current page consumed most narrow lines,
%   the next page had too few narrow lines left for the figure's y-range,
%   causing full-width text to overlap the deferred figure. Fix: extend
%   nl by the number of lines that fit in the remaining space on the
%   current page plus a buffer of 3. This guarantees enough narrow lines
%   carry over to cover the full figure height on the next page. Cost:
%   all text on the current page is narrowed (was already partially
%   narrowed), plus a few extra narrow lines below the figure on the
%   next page (minor cosmetic). Also fixed emergencystretch clobbering
%   (v3.16 carried forward).
%
% v3.16: Fixed emergencystretch clobbering. The Lua callback was
%   unconditionally resetting emergencystretch to 0 for every
%   non-wrapped paragraph, clobbering user-set values. Fix: save/restore
%   via swarmwrap@saved@es register; non-wrapped paragraphs no longer
%   touched.
%
% v3.15: Fixed deferred figure vertical alignment on next page. The
%   zero-height vbox placed by \afterpage caused a ~10pt gap between
%   the figure top and the first text line (TeX's \topskip glue).
%   Added \kern-\topskip after the vbox to eliminate this gap, so the
%   figure top now aligns with the first continuation text line.
%
% v3.14: Ghost narrowing mitigation — inter-narrow line penalties
%   are now boosted in post_linebreak_filter. Previously only the
%   boundary penalty (last narrow → first wide) was set high. Now
%   ALL penalties between consecutive narrow lines are boosted to
%   \swarmwrappenalty{N}, making TeX strongly prefer breaking before
%   or after the entire narrow zone. Reduces ghost narrowing from
%   potentially many lines to 0-1 lines in most cases.
%
% v3.13: Deferred figures now right-wrap on next page. Replaced the
%   v3.12 centered fallback with parshape + zero-height vbox overlay.
%   Parshape is applied in the deferred branch (same as NORMAL), so
%   continuation text on the next page is narrowed beside the figure.
%   The figure is placed via \afterpage using a zero-height vbox with
%   \smash{\rlap{}} to avoid consuming vertical space. Figure raise
%   is compensated for interline glue offset between the vbox and the
%   first continuation text line. Also fixed emergencystretch leak in
%   NORMAL branch by resetting swarmwrap@tw@lua to 0 after processing.
%
% v3.12: Fixed emergencystretch leak (partial — only DEFERRED path).
%
% v3.11: Fixed deferred figure placement. v3.10's overlaid deferred
%   figure caused text-figure overlap on the next page (full-width text
%   after parshape expiration collided with the overlaid figure). Now
%   when the figure doesn't fit, parshape is NOT applied (text flows at
%   full width) and the figure is deferred as a centered block via
%   \afterpage. Eliminates overlap, ghost narrowing, and clipping.
%
% v3.10: Deferred figure placement (overlaid via \afterpage). Re-added
%   afterpage dependency.
%
% v3.7: Reduced figure height padding from \baselineskip (13.6pt) to 4pt.
%   Eliminates 1 extra narrowed line below each figure that had no
%   figure beside it (visible empty strip).
%
% v3.6: Added \swarmwrappenalty{N} option (default 10000). Uses
%   LuaTeX post_linebreak_filter to insert a penalty at the boundary
%   between the last narrowed line and the first full-width line,
%   discouraging page breaks that cause ghost narrowing.
%
% v3.5: Non-LuaLaTeX compilation produces hard error (was silent fallback).
%   \swarmwrapnext errors on non-LuaLaTeX (was \relax).
%
% v3.4: Page-eject fallback replaces zero-height vbox. No more text-
%   figure overlap on page breaks.

\ProvidesPackage{swarmwrap}[2026/05/20 v3.30 Custom float wrapper]

\RequirePackage{graphicx}
\RequirePackage{ifluatex}

\newsavebox{\swarmwrap@box}
\newdimen\swarmwrap@fw       % figure width (auto-detected from box)
\newdimen\swarmwrap@fh       % figure height (auto-detected from box)
\newdimen\swarmwrap@tw       % text width (computed for parshape)
\newcount\swarmwrap@nl       % number of parshape lines (wrapped)
\newcount\swarmwrap@loop@cnt % loop counter
\newcount\swarmwrap@did@eject % eject flag (0=inline, 1=newpage issued)
\newcount\swarmwrapnl       % Lua-accessible copy of nl (for extension)
\newif\ifswarmwrap@luatex

\ifluatex \swarmwrap@luatextrue \else \swarmwrap@luatexfalse \fi

% Global macros to persist values across the environment group boundary.
\newcommand{\swarmwrap@fw@val}{0pt}  % figure width for parshape
\newcommand{\swarmwrap@fh@val}{0pt}  % figure height for page break

% ── Penalty control ──────────────────────────────────────────────────
% \swarmwrappenalty{N}: set the penalty inserted at the boundary between
% the last narrowed parshape line and the first full-width line, AND
% between all consecutive narrowed lines. Default: 100000 (prohibit
% page breaks within or at the boundary of the narrow zone). In TeX,
% penalties >= 10000 are 'infinite' and prevent breaks entirely.
% Set to 0 to allow breaks (no penalty). Set to 10000 to discourage.
% Set to -10000 to force a break.
\newcount\swarmwrap@penalty
\swarmwrap@penalty=100000

\newcommand{\swarmwrappenalty}[1]{%
  \swarmwrap@penalty=#1\relax
}

% Lua-readable register for the current wrapped text width.
% Set by \swarmwrapnext; read by the post_linebreak_filter callback.
\newdimen\swarmwrap@tw@lua
\swarmwrap@tw@lua=0pt

% Saved emergencystretch — restored after wrapped paragraph processing.
% Prevents clobbering user-set \emergencystretch values.
\newdimen\swarmwrap@saved@es
\swarmwrap@saved@es=0pt

% Remaining narrow lines counter (v3.25).
% TeX's \parshape only applies to ONE paragraph. When \lipsum[1]\lipsum[2]
% produces multiple paragraphs, only the first is narrowed. The fix: track
% how many narrow lines remain and use \everypar to re-inject \parshape
% at the start of each subsequent paragraph until the narrow zone is
% exhausted. This eliminates body-text overlaps (1543 in stress test)
% caused by full-width text from paragraph 2+ overlapping the figure.
\newcount\swarmwrap@remaining
\swarmwrap@remaining=0

% Command to set parshape for remaining lines (called from \everypar).
% Builds a dynamic parshape with \swarmwrap@remaining narrow lines + 1
% full-width line, then clears \everypar when remaining reaches 0.
% v3.29: Ghost narrowing fix — if a page was shipped since the last
% \swarmwrapnext (detected via shipout_filter flag), clear narrowing
% immediately. The figure (placed via \smash{\rlap{}}) is page-local
% and does NOT carry over to the continuation page.
\newcommand{\swarmwrap@set@parshape}{%
  \ifnum\swarmwrapremainingreg>0\relax
    % v3.29: Check if a page break occurred since \swarmwrapnext.
    % If so, the figure is gone — clear narrowing to prevent ghost.
    \directlua{%
      if swarmwrap_page_shipped then
        tex.count["swarmwrapremainingreg"] = 0
        texio.write_nl("log", "swarmwrap: ghost narrowing detected — clearing remaining")%
      end
    }%
    \ifnum\swarmwrapremainingreg>0\relax
      % CRITICAL: re-set \everypar for the NEXT paragraph.
      % TeX consumes \everypar after expansion — without this, only the
      % first paragraph gets narrowed. This was the root cause of 1420
      % overlaps in the stress test (v3.25-v3.27).
      \everypar{\swarmwrap@set@parshape}%
      \xdef\swarmwrap@pshape@dyn{\the\numexpr\swarmwrapremainingreg+1\relax\space}%
      \swarmwrap@loop@cnt=\swarmwrapremainingreg\relax
      \loop
        \xdef\swarmwrap@pshape@dyn{\swarmwrap@pshape@dyn 0pt \the\swarmwrap@tw\space}%
        \advance\swarmwrap@loop@cnt by -1\relax
      \ifnum\swarmwrap@loop@cnt>0 \repeat
      \xdef\swarmwrap@pshape@dyn{\swarmwrap@pshape@dyn 0pt \the\linewidth\space}%
      \parshape \swarmwrap@pshape@dyn\relax
    \else
      \everypar{}%  % Clear everypar — ghost narrowing prevented
    \fi
  \else
    \everypar{}%  % Clear everypar when narrow zone exhausted
  \fi
}

% ── \@item patch: inject \parshape before item labels (v3.26) ─────────
% Problem: \item's \everypar prepends \llap{label}\hskip\itemindent
% BEFORE our \swarmwrap@set@parshape. TeX reads \parshape at line-breaking
% time. If set in \everypar AFTER label material, it only applies from
% line 2. The first line of each \item is full-width, overlapping the figure.
% Fix: patch \@item to set \parshape BEFORE the label is processed.
% This ensures \parshape is active when TeX starts breaking lines.

\let\swarmwrap@orig@item=\@item

\def\@item{%
  \ifnum\swarmwrapremainingreg>0\relax
    % v3.29: Ghost narrowing check — clear if page was shipped.
    \directlua{%
      if swarmwrap_page_shipped then
        tex.count["swarmwrapremainingreg"] = 0
        texio.write_nl("log", "swarmwrap: ghost narrowing detected in @item — clearing remaining")%
      end
    }%
    \ifnum\swarmwrapremainingreg>0\relax
      % Set parshape BEFORE \@item processes the label.
      % This guarantees the first line of each item is narrowed.
      % Also re-set \everypar so subsequent items continue narrowing.
      \everypar{\swarmwrap@set@parshape}%
      \xdef\swarmwrap@pshape@dyn{\the\numexpr\swarmwrapremainingreg+1\relax\space}%
      \swarmwrap@loop@cnt=\swarmwrapremainingreg\relax
      \loop
        \xdef\swarmwrap@pshape@dyn{\swarmwrap@pshape@dyn 0pt \the\swarmwrap@tw\space}%
        \advance\swarmwrap@loop@cnt by -1\relax
      \ifnum\swarmwrap@loop@cnt>0 \repeat
      \xdef\swarmwrap@pshape@dyn{\swarmwrap@pshape@dyn 0pt \the\linewidth\space}%
      \parshape \swarmwrap@pshape@dyn\relax
    \fi
  \fi
  \swarmwrap@orig@item
}

% ── Lua callback: post_linebreak_filter ───────────────────────────────
% When a paragraph is broken into lines, this callback checks whether
% a parshape narrowing is active (swarmwrap@tw@lua > 0). If so, it
% boosts penalties between ALL consecutive narrow lines (not just at
% the boundary). This makes TeX strongly prefer to break before or
% after the entire narrow zone, reducing ghost narrowing on
% continuation pages from potentially many lines to 0-1 lines.

\ifswarmwrap@luatex
% Register TeX dimen/count registers for Lua access (no @ in names).
\newdimen\swarmwraptw
\newdimen\swarmwrapsavedes
\newcount\swarmwrappenaltyreg
\newcount\swarmwrapremainingreg
\directlua{texio.write_nl("term and log", "swarmwrap: INITIALIZING...")
  -- Per-paragraph wrapping state via FIFO queue.
  -- Each swarmwrap invocation pushes tw and saved_es;
  -- the callback shifts from the queue.
  -- This avoids the bug where tex.dimen reads the NEXT figure value.
  swarmwrap_queue = {}
  swarmwrap_qgen = 0

  -- Ghost narrowing detection: track whether a page has been shipped
  -- since the last \swarmwrapnext. If a page break occurs mid-wrap,
  -- the continuation page has no figure but parshape persists.
  -- Detection: shipout_filter sets this flag; \everypar checks it.
  swarmwrap_page_shipped = false
  -- v3.30: minimum tw across all figures on the current page.
  -- Used to clamp narrower figures' tw so text doesn't overlap
  -- wider figures still visible on the same page. Reset on page ship.
  swarmwrap_min_tw = 0
  -- v3.30: total narrow lines committed for the current page.
  -- When a new figure is placed, nl is extended to at least this value,
  -- ensuring text stays narrowed past ALL previous figures on the page.
  swarmwrap_page_nl = 0

  local function swarmwrap_shipout(head, groupcode)
    swarmwrap_page_shipped = true
    swarmwrap_min_tw = 0  -- Reset min tw tracking on page ship
    swarmwrap_page_nl = 0  -- Reset page nl tracking on page ship
    return head
  end
  luatexbase.add_to_callback("shipout_filter",
    swarmwrap_shipout, "swarmwrap: track page shipping")

  function swarmwrap_post_lb(head, groupcode)
    local entry = table.remove(swarmwrap_queue, 1)
    if not entry then
      return head
    end
    local tw_sp = entry.tw
    local remaining = entry.remaining or 0

    -- Count narrow lines in this paragraph
    local narrow_count = 0
    if tw_sp > 0 and remaining > 0 then
      local tw_val = tw_sp / 65536.0
      local tol = 3.0
      local narrow_width_max = tw_val + tol
      local current = head
      while current do
        if current.id == 0 then
          local lw = current.width / 65536.0
          if lw <= narrow_width_max and lw > 0 then
            narrow_count = narrow_count + 1
          end
        end
        current = current.next
      end
    end

    -- Update remaining counter via named register (accessible from TeX as
    -- \swarmwrapremainingreg and from Lua as tex.count["swarmwrapremainingreg"])
    remaining = math.max(0, remaining - narrow_count)
    tex.count["swarmwrapremainingreg"] = remaining

    -- v3.30: Update page-level narrow line tracking.
    -- Decrement by narrow lines consumed this paragraph.
    if swarmwrap_page_nl > 0 and narrow_count > 0 then
      swarmwrap_page_nl = math.max(0, swarmwrap_page_nl - narrow_count)
    end

    -- Apply penalties only for the FIRST paragraph (tw_sp > 0)
    if tw_sp > 0 then
      local penalty_val = tex.count["swarmwrappenaltyreg"]
      if penalty_val > 0 then
        local tw_val = tw_sp / 65536.0
        local tol = 3.0
        local narrow_width_max = tw_val + tol
        local last_narrow = nil
        local first_narrow = nil
        local last_penalty = nil
        local prev_of_first = nil  -- node before first narrow line
        local current = head
        while current do
          if current.id == node.id("penalty") then
            last_penalty = current
          elseif current.id == 0 then
            local lw = current.width / 65536.0
            local is_narrow = (lw <= narrow_width_max and lw > 0)
            if is_narrow then
              if not first_narrow then
                first_narrow = current
                prev_of_first = last_penalty
              end
              if last_penalty and last_penalty.penalty < penalty_val then
                last_penalty.penalty = penalty_val
              end
              last_narrow = current
            end
            last_penalty = nil
          end
          current = current.next
        end
        -- v3.29: Also insert penalty BEFORE the first narrow line.
        -- Without this, TeX can break just before the narrow zone,
        -- causing ghost narrowing on the continuation page.
        if first_narrow and not prev_of_first then
          local p = node.new(node.id("penalty"))
          p.penalty = penalty_val
          node.insert_before(head, first_narrow, p)
        end
        -- Insert penalty after the last narrow line (existing behavior).
        if last_narrow then
          local p = node.new(node.id("penalty"))
          p.penalty = penalty_val
          node.insert_after(head, last_narrow, p)
        end
      end
    end

    -- Restore saved emergencystretch
    tex.dimen["swarmwrapsavedes"] = entry.saved_es

    -- If narrow lines remain, push entry back for next paragraph
    if remaining > 0 then
      table.insert(swarmwrap_queue, {
        tw = tw_sp,
        saved_es = 0,
        remaining = remaining
      })
    end

    return head
  end
  luatexbase.add_to_callback("post_linebreak_filter",
    swarmwrap_post_lb, "swarmwrap: penalty at parshape boundary")
  texio.write_nl("term and log", "swarmwrap: DONE. queue=" .. tostring(swarmwrap_queue))
}
\fi

% ── Environment: capture content into a savebox (zero args) ────────────
% Content sets its natural width via explicit sizing:
%   - \includegraphics[width=3cm]{photo}  → box width = 3cm
%   - \begin{minipage}[t]{3cm}...        → box width = 3cm
% Width and height are measured from the rendered box after closing.

\newenvironment{swarmwrap}{%
  \ifswarmwrap@luatex
    \begin{lrbox}{\swarmwrap@box}%
  \else
    \PackageError{swarmwrap}{LuaLaTeX required for wrapping}{}%
  \fi
}{%
  \ifswarmwrap@luatex
    \end{lrbox}%
    % CRITICAL: Make the savebox global so it survives the group exit.
    \global\setbox\swarmwrap@box=\box\swarmwrap@box
    % Auto-detect width from rendered box
    \swarmwrap@fw=\wd\swarmwrap@box
    \xdef\swarmwrap@fw@val{\the\swarmwrap@fw}%
    % Auto-detect height from rendered box (+ small gap for visual spacing)
    \swarmwrap@fh=\ht\swarmwrap@box
    \advance\swarmwrap@fh by \dp\swarmwrap@box
    \advance\swarmwrap@fh by 4pt
    \xdef\swarmwrap@fh@val{\the\swarmwrap@fh}%
  \fi
}

% ── \swarmwrapnext: compute parshape and place figure ──────────────────
% All computation happens here so \linewidth is captured at the
% correct location (inside multicol, itemize, etc.).
%
% Figure placement strategy (v3.23):
%   1. Compute parshape from full figure height (text always stays).
%   2. Check if figure fits: \pagegoal - \pagetotal >= figure height.
%   3. If fits → place inline with \smash{\rlap{}}.
%   4. If doesn't fit → \newpage, then place inline (same as step 3).
%      The figure appears at the top-right of the new page, and text
%      wraps beside it via parshape. No afterpage needed.

\ifswarmwrap@luatex
\newcommand{\swarmwrapnext}{%
  % ── Shared computation: text width and wrapped line count ───────
  \swarmwrap@fw=\swarmwrap@fw@val\relax
  \swarmwrap@tw=\linewidth
  \advance\swarmwrap@tw by -\swarmwrap@fw
  \advance\swarmwrap@tw by -14pt
  \swarmwrap@fh=\swarmwrap@fh@val\relax
  % Compute nl using ROUNDING (not ceiling) to reduce "1 line too much".
  % Combined with multi-paragraph parshape (v3.25), this provides a good
  % balance: narrow zone covers most of the figure while minimizing
  % layout shifts that cause consecutive-figure overlaps.
  \dimen2=\baselineskip
  \divide\dimen2 by 2
  \swarmwrap@nl=0
  \dimen0=\swarmwrap@fh
  \advance\dimen0 by \dimen2
  \loop
    \advance\swarmwrap@nl by 1
    \advance\dimen0 by -\baselineskip
  \ifdim\dimen0>0pt \repeat
  \advance\swarmwrap@nl by -1
  % v3.30: Initialize \swarmwrapnl from computed nl.
  % This will be extended below by swarmwrap_page_nl for consecutive figures.
  \global\swarmwrapnl=\swarmwrap@nl\relax
  \xdef\swarmwrap@tw@val{\the\swarmwrap@tw}%
  % Set Lua-readable dimension for post_linebreak_filter callback
  \global\swarmwrap@tw@lua=\swarmwrap@tw\relax
  % ── Figure placement: inline or page-eject then inline ──────────
  % Check remaining space on current page.
  \dimen0=\pagegoal
  \advance\dimen0 by -\pagetotal
  \dimen1=\swarmwrap@fh@val\relax
  \swarmwrap@did@eject=0\relax
  \ifdim\dimen0<\dimen1
    % Figure doesn't fit — eject to new page first.
    \newpage
    \swarmwrap@did@eject=1\relax
    % v3.30 FIX: The shipout_filter fires during \newpage and sets
    % swarmwrap_page_shipped=true. This causes the ghost narrowing
    % check in \swarmwrap@set@parshape to clear remaining, preventing
    % parshape from being applied on the new page. Reset the flag.
    \directlua{swarmwrap_page_shipped = false}%
  \fi
  % v3.30 FIX: Consecutive figure overlap prevention.
  % When two figures are on the same page and the second is NARROWER
  % (e.g., 2cm then 3cm), the second figure's tw (text width) is WIDER
  % than the first's. Text narrowed for the second figure extends into
  % the first figure's area, causing overlap. Fix: track the minimum tw
  % (swarmwrap_min_tw) across all figures on the current page. When a
  % new figure's tw exceeds the minimum, clamp it. Reset on page ship.
  % IMPORTANT: This must run BEFORE parshape build and queue insert so
  % that parshape, figure placement, and Lua callback all use the
  % clamped value.
  % Copy tw to Lua-accessible bridge register (no @ for safe Lua access).
  \global\swarmwraptw=\swarmwrap@tw\relax
  % v3.30 FIX: Consecutive figure overlap prevention.
  % Clamp tw to the minimum across all figures on the current page.
  % When a new figure is narrower (e.g., 2cm) than a previous figure
  % (e.g., 5cm), the new figure's tw is wider, causing text to extend
  % into the previous figure's area. Fix: clamp tw to the page minimum.
  % Reset on page ship via shipout_filter.
  \directlua{swarmwrap_min_tw=(swarmwrap_min_tw or 0);local ctw=tex.dimen["swarmwraptw"] or 0;if ctw>0 and swarmwrap_min_tw>0 and ctw>swarmwrap_min_tw then tex.dimen["swarmwraptw"]=swarmwrap_min_tw end;local etw=tex.dimen["swarmwraptw"] or 0;if swarmwrap_min_tw==0 or etw<swarmwrap_min_tw then swarmwrap_min_tw=etw end}%
  % Copy clamped tw back to \swarmwrap@tw so parshape and overlay
  % use the clamped value. CRITICAL: without this, parshape uses the
  % unclamped tw, allowing text to extend into previous figure zones.
  \global\swarmwrap@tw=\swarmwraptw\relax
  % Re-save tw@val and tw@lua AFTER clamping.
  \xdef\swarmwrap@tw@val{\the\swarmwrap@tw}%
  \global\swarmwrap@tw@lua=\swarmwrap@tw
  % v3.30: Extend nl to cover remaining narrow lines from previous
  % figures on the same page. When Figure A (5cm, 10 lines) is followed
  % by Figure B (3cm, 5 lines) on the same page, B's narrow zone must
  % cover A's remaining height + B's own height. Without this, B's text
  % returns to full width while A's figure zone is still visible.
  % swarmwrap_page_nl tracks remaining lines from all previous figures.
  \directlua{%
    local pnl = swarmwrap_page_nl or 0
    if pnl > 0 then
      local cur_nl = tex.count["swarmwrapnl"]
      tex.count["swarmwrapnl"] = cur_nl + pnl
      swarmwrap_page_nl = cur_nl + pnl
    else
      swarmwrap_page_nl = tex.count["swarmwrapnl"]
    end
  }%
  % NORMAL PATH: place figure inline with parshape wrapping.
  % (After potential \newpage, figure is at top of a fresh page.)
  % Build parshape: nl narrow lines + 1 full-width line.
  % v3.30: Use \swarmwrapnl (possibly extended) instead of \swarmwrap@nl.
  \xdef\swarmwrap@pshape{\the\numexpr\swarmwrapnl+1\relax\space}%
  \swarmwrap@loop@cnt=\swarmwrapnl
  \loop
    \xdef\swarmwrap@pshape{\swarmwrap@pshape 0pt \the\swarmwrap@tw\space}%
    \advance\swarmwrap@loop@cnt by -1
  \ifnum\swarmwrap@loop@cnt>0 \repeat
  \xdef\swarmwrap@pshape{\swarmwrap@pshape 0pt \the\linewidth\space}%
  % emergencystretch absorbs overfull hbox on narrowed parshape lines
  % Save pre-existing emergencystretch before overwriting.
  \swarmwrap@saved@es=\emergencystretch
  \emergencystretch=\fontdimen6\font\relax
  % Set remaining counter and Lua-readable register.
  % This tracks how many narrow lines are left across paragraphs.
  \global\swarmwrap@remaining=\swarmwrapnl
  \global\swarmwrapremainingreg=\swarmwrapnl
  % Push wrapping state onto Lua queue BEFORE \noindent.
  % Also reset the page-shipped flag so ghost narrowing detection
  % starts fresh for this figure.
  \directlua{%
    if swarmwrap_queue == nil then
      texio.write_nl("term and log", "swarmwrap BUG: queue is nil! Resetting.")
      swarmwrap_queue = {}
    end
    swarmwrap_page_shipped = false
    table.insert(swarmwrap_queue, {%
      tw = tex.dimen["swarmwraptw"],%
      saved_es = tex.dimen["swarmwrap@saved@es"],%
      remaining = tonumber(tex.count["swarmwrapremainingreg"])%
    })%
  }%
  % Set \everypar to re-inject parshape for subsequent paragraphs.
  % TeX's \parshape only applies to ONE paragraph. This ensures the
  % narrowing continues across \lipsum[1]\lipsum[2] paragraph boundaries.
  \everypar{\swarmwrap@set@parshape}%
  \noindent
  \parshape \swarmwrap@pshape\relax
  \smash{\rlap{\hskip\swarmwrap@tw@val\hskip14pt\raise\dimexpr\ht\strutbox-\ht\swarmwrap@box\relax\hbox{\copy\swarmwrap@box}}}%
  \wlog{swarmwrap next: \ifnum\swarmwrap@did@eject=1 EJECT\else INLINE\fi — tw=\the\swarmwrap@tw, fh=\the\swarmwrap@fh, nl=\the\swarmwrap@nl, remaining=\the\dimen0}%
}%
\else
\newcommand{\swarmwrapnext}{%
  \PackageError{swarmwrap}{LuaLaTeX required for wrapping. Text wrapping is not supported on pdfLaTeX/XeLaTeX. Either compile with lualatex, or remove swarmwrap.}{}%
}%
\fi

\endinput
